iguel, Pedro, Roberto.","Spanish (<b>Díaz</b>): patronymic from the medieval personal name <i>Didacus</i> (see   Diego  ).","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the Spanish surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Diazdeleon","meanings":["Spanish: combination of the surname <b>Díaz</b> (see   Diaz  ) and the name León (see   Leon  ) with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’."]},{"name":"Diego","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Francisco, Juan, Fernando, Jose, Miguel, Mario, Maximo, Salvador, Aida, Ana, Domingo.","Spanish: from the very common male personal name <i>Diego</i>, which in the Spanish-speaking world is usually taken to be a shortened form of   Santiago  . However, this may be only a folk etymology. The personal name is found in the Middle Ages in the Latin forms <i>Didacus</i> and <i>Didagus</i>, probably a derivative of Greek <i>didachē</i> ‘doctrine, teaching’. However, in view of the fact that this personal name is unknown outside the Iberian Peninsula, it may actually have a pre-Roman origin."]},{"name":"Diez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Juan, Fernando, Pedro, Rafael, Roberto, Angel, Eduardo, Mario, Ricardo.","Spanish (<b>Díez</b>): variant of <b>Díaz</b> (see   Diaz  ).","German: variant of   Dietz  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sandoval","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Carlos, Manuel, Luis, Francisco, Ruben, Pedro, Miguel, Raul, Mario.","Spanish: habitational name from any of the places called Sandoval, in particular the one in Burgos, also those in Murcia and Málaga, earlier called <i>Sannoval</i>, from Latin <i>saltus</i> ‘grove’, ‘wood’ + <i>novalis</i> ‘newly cleared land’. In the US, this surname is also found among Native Americans (Navajos)."],"variants":[{"name":"Sandobal","meanings":["Spanish: variant of   Sandoval  ."]}]},{"name":"Gutierre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Ramon, Jesus, Juan, Manuel, Alberto, Alfonzo, Alvaro, Ana, Andres, Antelmo, Catalina.","Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Gutiérrez</b> (see   Gutierrez  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Gutierrez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Luis, Jesus, Manuel, Carlos, Francisco, Jorge, Pedro, Raul, Miguel, Roberto.","Spanish (<b>Gutiérrez</b>): patronymic from the medieval personal name <i>Gutierre</i>, from a Visigothic personal name of uncertain form and meaning, perhaps a compound of the elements <i>gunthi</i> ‘battle’ + <i>hairus</i> ‘sword’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gutierre Diaz  de Sandoval was born about 1146, his father, Rodrigo Fernández de Sandoval, was 27 and his mother, Mrs Rodrigo Fernandez De Sandoval, was 8. He married Ines de Rada about 1170, in Spain. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died about 1196, at the age of 52."},"et":{"ABT 1146–ABT 1196":"umbes 1146–umbes 1196","1146–1196":"1146–1196","1148–Female":"1148–Surnud","11